\i \cf0 Amplify
\i0  is a Mac program for simulating DNA amplification by the polymerase chain reaction. You supply the DNA sequences of one or more primers plus a length of target DNA sequence, and 
\i Amplify
\i0  will generate a map of the expected outcome. It will also provide other helpful information such as the sequences of likely amplified fragments, warnings about potential primer dimers, etc.\
\

\i Amplify
\i0  is useful for planning experiments and for teaching students about PCR.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri0

\f1\fs44 \cf0 \cb5 \uc0\u9670 
\f2  Overview: How to use 
\i Amplify\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\i0\fs28 \cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Step 1: Open text files with the target and primer sequences\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
You need to tell 
\i Amplify
\i0  the DNA sequences of the target area plus those of one or more primers. Primers are short fragments of synthesized DNA, typically around 20 bp. The target is usually a stretch of sequence from the genome of an organism whose DNA you want to amplify. \
\
If you want to test 
\i Amplify
\i0  but don't have any target or primer sequences handy, just select 
\b Open Built-In Samples
\b0  from the 
\b File
\b0  menu.\
\
Go to the 
\b File
\i  
\i0\b0 menu and select 
\b Open
\b0  (
\f1 \uc0\u8984 
\f2 -O) to open your text files containing the target and/or the primer sequences. These can simple text files with the extension \'93.txt\'94 or more specific files like \'93.rtf\'94, \'93.csv\'94, \'93.primers\'94, \'93.pri\'94 and others. See below for more details about file formats.\
\
When you select a text file to open, 
\i Amplify
\i0  will know whether it contains the target sequence or a list of primers. (How does it know? It can usually tell by the file extension. If not, it checks to see whether the file \'93looks\'94 like a list of primers which typically has multiple lines with one or more tab characters per line.) When you open the target sequence, 
\i Amplify
\i0  will display it on the left side of the screen. The list of primers will go on the right.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Step 2: Select one or more primers from the list\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
To the left of each primer sequence you will see a checkbox. You must check at least one to run a PCR, but you can check as many as you like. \
\
One way to mark a set of primers is to start by selecting them using the 
\f1 \uc0\u8984 
\f2 -click, then choose 
\b Check
\b0  from the popup menu, 
\b Selected
\b0 , above the primer list.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Step 3: Run the PCR simulation\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
When you choose 
\b Amplify
\b0  from the 
\b PCR
\b0  menu (
\f1 \uc0\u8984 
\f2 -1), 
\i Amplify
\i0  will draw a map of the expected outcome. You can now click on items in this drawing to get more information about each.\
\
You can also save or print the results. The results consist of the map in the top half of the window and the textual output in the bottom half. You save and print these two halves separately.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri0

\f1\fs44 \cf0 \cb5 \uc0\u9670 
\f2  The 
\i Amplify
\i0  Windows\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\fs28 \cf0 \cb1 \
There are two kinds of windows in 
\i Amplify
\i0 . One, the substrate window, contains the information you supply: the target sequence and the primers. The other, the PCR results window, contains the results of 
\i Amplify
\i0 's simulated PCR.\
\
The substrate window is the one that shows up when you first open the program. It consists of a left and right portion with a "split window" vertical bar between them. You can move this vertical bar left and right to alter the relative size of the two parts. You can also resize the whole window. The left side contains the target sequence and the right side has the primer list.\
\
When you run a simulated PCR (
\f1 \uc0\u8984 
\f2 -1) a new PCR window will be generated. It also consists of two parts -- an upper part with the amplification map and a lower part with textual output. There is a moveable separator bar between them. The map is described in more detail below. The textual output contains information you request by clicking on elements of the map. \
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri0

\f1\fs44 \cf0 \cb5 \uc0\u9670 
\f2  Target Sequence\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\fs28 \cf0 \cb1 \
The target sequence for amplification appears as editable text in the left half of the substrate window. You can add a sequence to by copying and pasting, or else by opening a text file.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

