\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Sequence headers\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf6 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 Some sequence files come with a preamble or header before the actual sequence begins. 
\i Amplify
\i0  assumes that there is a specific string that separates the header from the rest of the sequence. You can set this header string to be whatever you like in the "Preferences" dialog. For example, a delimiter string might be "End Header" or "..". Having a sequence header is optional.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Styled text in target sequence\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf6 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\i\b0\fs28 \cf0 Amplify
\i0  allows you to mark specified parts of your target by changing the color or setting the text as boldface or italicization. This feature is handy for marking areas of interest. These styles have no effect on the amplification. You are also free to use upper or lower case letters. \
\
You should use only color and text style to mark bases, however. The font and size should be uniform throughout the target sequence in order for the base count numbers to the left of the sequence to be accurate. You can, however, select a different font and size for the 
\i entire
\i0  target sequence. Do this with the popup menus above the target sequence. Note that only monospaced fonts should be used.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Allowable characters\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf6 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 The actual sequence part of the text (i.e., the text following any sequence header) must consist of the letters A, T, C, G or N (or a, t, c, g or n). Any other characters will be removed. Note that other IUB codes are allowed in the primer specifications but not in the target sequence.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Inversion\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf6 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 You can invert any selected portion of the target sequence by choosing 
\b Flip Selected Bases
\b0  from the 
\b DNA
\b0  popup menu above the target. Note that 
\i Amplify
\i0  remembers the text style (color, etc.) of each character during the inversion.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Selecting a range of bases\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf6 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\b0\fs28 \cf0 Under the 
\b DNA 
\b0 popup menu is 
\b Select Base Range\'85
\b0  which allows you to enter the first and last base of a range to be selected in the target sequence. \
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri0

\f1\fs44 \cf0 \cb5 \uc0\u9670 
\f2  Primer List\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

\fs28 \cf0 \cb1 \
The list of your available primers appears on the right side of the substrate window. It has columns for the primer's sequence, its name and any other "notes" you might want to include. \
\
Your primers can be stored in a tab-delimited text file and opened within 
\i Amplify
\i0  with the 
\b Open
\b0  selection (
\f1 \uc0\u8984 
\f2 -O) under the 
\b File
\b0  menu.\
\
You can change the total width of the list, and also resize the individual columns by dragging the boundaries.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li270\ri-19445

\f4 \cf2 \'95
\f2\b\fs36  Columns in the primer list
\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445
\cf0 \
The \ul sequence\ulnone  can include any of the IUB standard base codes: G, A, T, C and the ambiguous codes, M, R, W, S, Y, K, V, H, D, B and N. They can be upper or lower case, and are written in standard 5\uc0\u8242  \u8594  3\u8242  order. The primer sequence can be of any length.\
\
The \ul primer\ulnone  names should be short, usually no more than 10 characters, so that they don't overlap when displayed on the map. \
\
The \ul notes\ulnone  column can have whatever textual information you want. This column isn't used in the PCR simulation, but you can use it for searching, selecting and organizing your primer list.\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\li576\ri-19445

